## Diagnosis

The `micro` rendering mode was introduced as a progressive-disclosure pattern — show *something* in every tile regardless of size. But 8 px type is below the threshold of legibility (~11 px minimum for body copy, ~9 px absolute floor for any rendered text). The result is text that is technically present but practically invisible, which is worse than showing nothing because it creates visual noise without communicating information.

---

## Root Cause

**Anti-pattern AP-072 — Legibility Sacrifice for Density Completeness.**

The component tries to render a label in *every* tile at *every* size, forcing the font down rather than hiding content gracefully. The correct contract is:

> If a tile is too small to render readable text, render *no text* — not illegible text.

---

## Fix

### 1. Remove the `micro` branch entirely from the tile renderer

**`components/knowledge/KnowledgeTreemap.tsx`** (or wherever `renderTileContent` / the tile component lives):

```tsx
// BEFORE — three modes, micro is broken
function getTileMode(width: number, height: number): 'micro' | 'compact' | 'full' {
  const area = width * height;
  if (width < 64 || height < 32) return 'micro';   // ← DELETE this branch
  if (area < 8000)               return 'compact';
  return 'full';
}

// AFTER — two modes: show readable text or show nothing
function getTileMode(width: number, height: number): 'hidden' | 'compact' | 'full' {
  // Below these dimensions no text is legible; suppress it entirely.
  const MIN_READABLE_WIDTH  = 64;   // px — fits ~6 chars at 11px
  const MIN_READABLE_HEIGHT = 28;   // px — fits one line + 4px padding
  const area = width * height;

  if (width < MIN_READABLE_WIDTH || height < MIN_READABLE_HEIGHT) return 'hidden';
  if (area < 8000) return 'compact';
  return 'full';
}
```

### 2. Update the tile renderer to respect `hidden`

```tsx
// BEFORE
function TileLabel({ node, width, height }: TileLabelProps) {
  const mode = getTileMode(width, height);

  if (mode === 'micro') {
    return (
      <span className="text-[8px] leading-none truncate opacity-60">
        {node.name}
      </span>
    );
  }
  // … compact / full …
}

// AFTER
function TileLabel({ node, width, height }: TileLabelProps) {
  const mode = getTileMode(width, height);

  // Tile is too small to render legible text — render nothing.
  // The tile itself (colour + tooltip) still communicates identity.
  if (mode === 'hidden') return null;

  if (mode === 'compact') {
    return (
      <span className="text-xs leading-tight truncate font-medium">
        {node.name}
      </span>
    );
  }

  // full
  return (
    <div className="flex flex-col gap-0.5 min-w-0">
      <span className="text-sm font-semibold leading-tight truncate">
        {node.name}
      </span>
      {node.count != null && (
        <span className="text-xs text-foreground/60 tabular-nums">
          {node.count}
        </span>
      )}
    </div>
  );
}
```

### 3. Ensure small tiles still communicate via tooltip

Small tiles must not become *silent* — they need a tooltip so the information is still accessible. If that isn't already in place:

```tsx
// In the tile wrapper (wherever <Tooltip> / title attr is set)
<div
  title={node.name}                        // native fallback
  aria-label={node.name}                   // screen reader
  className="relative overflow-hidden ..."
>
  <TileLabel node={node} width={width} height={height} />
</div>
```

If you use Radix `<Tooltip>` or a similar primitive, confirm it wraps *every* tile, not just the ones that have a visible label.

### 4. Delete the `micro` token from your Tailwind config (if it was added there)

**`tailwind.config.ts`** — remove the stray font-size entry if it was ever codified:

```ts
// Remove this if present:
fontSize: {
  micro: ['8px', { lineHeight: '1' }],   // ← DELETE
  // …
}
```

Running `grep -r "micro\|text-\[8px\]" components/` will confirm you've caught every callsite.

---

## Principle

**Show nothing before showing something unreadable.**

Progressive disclosure in data-dense UIs has a hard floor: the moment a content element drops below legibility, suppress it — don't scale it down further. The *tile* (its colour, its position, its tooltip) continues to encode information at any size. Text only adds value when it can actually be read.

Operationally, express this as a named constant (`MIN_READABLE_WIDTH / HEIGHT`) rather than a magic number buried in a conditional, so the threshold is a single source of truth and future contributors can see the reasoning.

> Corollary: never add a font-size token below 11 px to the design-system token set. If you find yourself needing one, the layout is wrong, not the type scale.
